[src:promql/complex-event-processing] These events may be happening across the various layers of an organization as sales leads, orders or customer service calls.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Or, they may be news items, text messages, social media posts, business processes (such as supply chain), traffic reports, weather reports, or other kinds of data.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] An event may also be defined as a "change of state," when a measurement exceeds a predefined threshold of time, temperature, or other value.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Analysts have suggested that CEP will give organizations a new way to analyze patterns in real-time and help the business side communicate better with IT and service departments.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] CEP has since become an enabling technology in many systems that are used to take immediate action in response to incoming streams of events.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Applications are now to be found (2018) in many sectors of business including stock market trading systems, mobile devices, internet operations, fraud detection, the transportation industry, and governmental intelligence gathering.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] The vast amount of information available about events is sometimes referred to as the event cloud.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] 2. the appearance of a man in a tuxedo with a woman in a flowing white gown.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] From these events the monitoring system may infer a *complex event*: a wedding.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] CEP as a technique helps discover complex events by analyzing and correlating other events: the bells, the man and woman in wedding attire and the rice flying through the air.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Commercial applications of CEP exist in variety of industries and include the detection of credit-card fraud, business activity monitoring, and security monitoring.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] The CEP area has roots in discrete event simulation, the active database area and some programming languages.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] The activity in the industry was preceded by a wave of research projects in the 1990s.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] According to the first project that paved the way to a generic CEP language and execution model was the Rapide project in Stanford University, directed by David Luckham.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] In parallel there have been two other research projects: Infospheres in California Institute of Technology, directed by K.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Mani Chandy, and Apama in University of Cambridge directed by John Bates.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] The commercial products were dependents of the concepts developed in these and some later research projects.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Community efforts started in a series of event processing symposia organized by the Event Processing Technical Society, and later by the ACM DEBS conference series.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] One of the community efforts was to produce the event processing manifesto.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] CEP is used in operational intelligence (OI) products to provide insight into business operations by running query analysis against live feeds and event data.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] OI collects real-time data and correlates against historical data to provide insight and analysis.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Multiple sources of data can be combined to provide a common operating picture that uses current information.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] In network management, systems management, application management and service management, people usually refer instead to event correlation.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] As CEP engines, event correlation engines (*event correlators*) analyze a mass of events, pinpoint the most significant ones, and trigger actions.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] However, most of them do not produce new inferred events.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Instead, they relate high-level events with low-level events.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Inference engines, e.g., rule-based reasoning engines, typically produce inferred information in artificial intelligence.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] However, they do not usually produce new information in the form of complex (i.e., inferred) events.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] A more systemic example of CEP involves a car, some sensors and various events and reactions.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Imagine that a car has several sensors—one that measures tire pressure, one that measures speed, and one that detects if someone sits on a seat or leaves a seat.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] In the first situation, the car is moving and the pressure of one of the tires moves from 45 psi to 41 psi over 15 minutes.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] As the pressure in the tire is decreasing, a series of events containing the tire pressure is generated.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] In addition, a series of events containing the speed of the car is generated.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] The car's Event Processor may detect a situation whereby a loss of tire pressure over a relatively long period of time results in the creation of the "lossOfTirePressure" event.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] This new event may trigger a reaction process to note the pressure loss into the car's maintenance log, and alert the driver via the car's portal that the tire pressure has reduced.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] In the second situation, the car is moving and the pressure of one of the tires drops from 45 psi to 20 psi in 5 seconds.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] A different situation is detected—perhaps because the loss of pressure occurred over a shorter period of time, or perhaps because the difference in values between each event were larger than a predefined limit.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] The different situation results in a new event "blowOutTire" being generated.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] This new event triggers a different reaction process to immediately alert the driver and to initiate onboard computer routines to assist the driver in bringing the car to a stop without losing control through skidding.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] In addition, events that represent detected situations can also be combined with other events in order to detect more complex situations.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] For example, in the final situation the car is moving normally and suffers a blown tire which results in the car leaving the road and striking a tree, and the driver is thrown from the car.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] A series of different situations are rapidly detected.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] The combination of "blowOutTire", "zeroSpeed" and "driverLeftSeat" within a very short period of time results in a new situation being detected: "occupantThrownAccident".
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Even though there is no direct measurement that can determine conclusively that the driver was thrown, or that there was an accident, the combination of events allows the situation to be detected and a new event to be created to signify the detected situation.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] This is the essence of a complex (or composite) event.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] It is complex because one cannot directly detect the situation; one has to infer or deduce that the situation has occurred from a combination of other events.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] A natural fit for CEP has been with business process management (BPM).
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] BPM focuses on end-to-end business processes, in order to continuously optimize and align for its operational environment.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] However, the optimization of a business does not rely solely upon its individual, end-to-end processes.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Seemingly disparate processes can affect each other significantly.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Consider this scenario: In the aerospace industry, it is good practice to monitor breakdowns of vehicles to look for trends (determine potential weaknesses in manufacturing processes, material, etc.).
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Another separate process monitors current operational vehicles' life cycles and decommissions them when appropriate.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] The integration of CEP and BPM must exist at two levels, both at the business awareness level (users must understand the potential holistic benefits of their individual processes) and also at the technological level (there needs to be a method by which CEP can interact with BPM implementation).
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] For a recent state of the art review on the integration of CEP with BPM, which is frequently labeled as Event-Driven Business Process Management, refer to.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Computation-oriented CEP's role can arguably be seen to overlap with Business Rule technology.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] For example, customer service centers are using CEP for click-stream analysis and customer experience management.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] CEP software can factor real-time information about millions of events (clicks or other interactions) per second into business intelligence and other decision-support applications.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] These "recommendation applications" help agents provide personalized service based on each customer's experience.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] The CEP application may collect data about what customers on the phone are currently doing, or how they have recently interacted with the company in other various channels, including in-branch, or on the Web via self-service features, instant messaging and email.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] The application then analyzes the total customer experience and recommends scripts or next steps that guide the agent on the phone, and hopefully keep the customer happy.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] A time series database is a software system that is optimized for the handling of data organized by time.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Time series are finite or infinite sequences of data items, where each item has an associated timestamp and the sequence of timestamps is non-decreasing.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Elements of a time series are often called ticks.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] The timestamps are not required to be ascending (merely non-decreasing) because in practice the time resolution of some systems such as financial data sources can be quite low (milliseconds, microseconds or even nanoseconds), so consecutive events may carry equal timestamps.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Time series data provides a historical context to the analysis typically associated with complex event processing.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] This can apply to any vertical industry such as finance and cooperatively with other technologies such as BPM.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] The ideal case for CEP analysis is to view historical time series and real-time streaming data as a single time continuum.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] What happened yesterday, last week or last month is simply an extension of what is occurring today and what may occur in the future.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] An example may involve comparing current market volumes to historic volumes, prices and volatility for trade execution logic.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Or the need to act upon live market prices may involve comparisons to benchmarks that include sector and index movements, whose intra-day and historic trends gauge volatility and smooth outliers.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Complex event processing is a key enabler in Internet of things (IoT) settings and smart cyber-physical systems (CPS) as well.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Processing dense and heterogeneous streams from various sensors and matching patterns against those streams is a typical task in such cases.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] The majority of these techniques rely on the fact that representing the IoT system's state and its changes is more efficient in the form of a data stream, instead of having a static, materialized model.
[src:promql/complex-event-processing] Reasoning over such stream-based models fundamentally differs from traditional reasoning techniques and typically require the combination of model transformations and CEP.
[src:promql/data-stream] In connection-oriented communication, a **data stream** is the transmission of a sequence of digitally encoded signals to convey information.
[src:promql/data-stream] Typically, the transmitted symbols are grouped into a series of packets.
[src:promql/data-stream] Most data transmitted over the Internet is transmitted as a data stream.
[src:promql/data-stream] Using a mobile phone to have a conversation transmits the sound as a data stream.
[src:promql/data-stream] 2. $\Delta$ is a sequence of positive real time intervals.
[src:promql/data-stream] Data Stream contains different sets of data, that depend on the chosen data format.
[src:promql/data-stream] A **data point** is a tag that collects information about a certain action, performed by a user on a website.
[src:promql/data-stream] Data points exists in two types, the values of which are used to create appropriate audiences.
[src:promql/data-stream] Information gathered out of websites are based on user behavior.
[src:promql/data-stream] Data providers deliver both personal or non-personal information.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Prometheus originated at SoundCloud in 2012 and was accepted by the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) in 2016, graduating from incubation in 2018.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] It is commonly paired with Grafana for dashboard visualization and supports a wide range of exporters and integrations.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Prometheus was developed at SoundCloud starting in 2012, after the company found that its existing metrics tools, based on StatsD and Graphite, could not meet the demands of its containerized infrastructure.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] The design goals included a multi-dimensional data model, operational simplicity, scalable data collection, and a powerful query language in a single tool.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] The project was open source from the start and was adopted by Boxever and Docker users before any official announcement.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] The design was influenced by Borgmon, Google's internal time-series monitoring system, which treated time-series data as a source for alert generation.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] By 2013, Prometheus was in production use at SoundCloud.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] The project was publicly announced in January 2015.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] In May 2016, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation accepted Prometheus as its second incubated project, after Kubernetes.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] In August 2018, the CNCF announced that Prometheus had graduated from incubation.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Prometheus 1.0 was released in July 2016.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Subsequent releases through 2016 and 2017 led to Prometheus 2.0 in November 2017, which introduced a new storage engine with significantly improved performance and reduced disk usage.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] A typical Prometheus monitoring deployment consists of several components working together.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Exporters run on monitored hosts to collect and expose local metrics.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] The Prometheus server scrapes those exporters at a configured interval, aggregates the data, and stores it locally.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Alertmanager receives alerts from Prometheus and handles routing, grouping, and silencing before forwarding notifications.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Grafana is commonly used to build dashboards from Prometheus data.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Queries against all of these are written in PromQL, Prometheus's native query language.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Prometheus data is organized as named metrics, each optionally qualified by an arbitrary number of key-value label pairs.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Labels can identify the data source (server name, datacenter) or carry application-specific context such as HTTP status code, request method, or endpoint.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Querying in real time against any combination of labels is what makes the data model multi-dimensional.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Prometheus stores data locally on disk for fast writes and queries.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Metrics can also be forwarded to remote storage backends, including Grafana Mimir and other Prometheus-compatible systems.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Prometheus collects data through a pull model: the server periodically queries a configured list of targets (exporters) and aggregates the returned time-series values.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Prometheus includes several service discovery mechanisms to automatically locate targets in dynamic environments.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Prometheus provides its own query language, PromQL (Prometheus Query Language), which allows users to select and aggregate time-series data.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] The language includes time-oriented constructs such as the rate() function, instant vectors, and range vectors that return multiple samples per series over a specified time window.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Alert rules in Prometheus specify a condition and a duration; if the condition holds for that duration, Prometheus fires an alert to Alertmanager.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Alertmanager handles silencing, inhibition, and routing to notification destinations including email, Slack, and PagerDuty.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Additional targets such as Microsoft Teams can be reached through the Alertmanager webhook receiver interface.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Prometheus includes its own time series database.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Recent data (by default, one to three hours) is held in a combination of memory and mmap-backed files.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Older data is written to persistent blocks indexed with an inverted index, which suits Prometheus's label-based query patterns.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] A background compaction process merges smaller blocks into larger ones to reduce read overhead.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Durability against crashes is provided by a write-ahead log (WAL).
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Prometheus includes a basic expression browser but is not a full dashboard system.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Grafana is the standard pairing, querying Prometheus via PromQL to produce dashboards; the need to deploy and maintain Grafana separately is sometimes cited as an operational drawback.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Prometheus favors white-box monitoring, where applications publish internal metrics for collection.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Exporters and agents are available for many applications and systems.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] For transition from existing monitoring stacks, Prometheus supports several protocols: Graphite, StatsD, SNMP, JMX, and CollectD.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Metrics are typically retained for a few weeks.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] For longer retention, Prometheus can stream data to remote storage backends.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] An effort to standardize the Prometheus exposition format as OpenMetrics has gained adoption from several vendors, including InfluxData's TICK suite, InfluxDB, Google Cloud Platform, Datadog, and New Relic.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] The OpenMetrics specification is maintained separately from the Prometheus project.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] Prometheus client libraries are available for most major programming languages.
[src:promql/prometheus-software] The POCO C++ Libraries expose Prometheus metrics through the `Poco::Prometheus` namespace.
[src:promql/query-language] A **query language**, also known as **data query language** or **database query language** (**DQL**), is a computer language used to make queries in databases and information systems.
[src:promql/query-language] In database systems, query languages rely on strict theory to retrieve information.
[src:promql/query-language] A well known example is the Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:promql/query-language] Broadly, query languages can be classified according to whether they are *database* query languages or *information retrieval* query languages.
[src:promql/query-language] The difference is that a **database query language** attempts to give factual answers to factual questions, while an **information retrieval query language** attempts to find documents containing information that is relevant to an area of inquiry.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] A **regular expression** (shortened as **regex** or **regexp**), sometimes referred to as a **rational expression**, is a sequence of characters that specifies a match pattern in text.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Usually such patterns are used by string-searching algorithms for "find" or "find and replace" operations on strings, or for input validation.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Regular expression techniques are developed in theoretical computer science and formal language theory.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The concept of regular expressions began in the 1950s, when the American mathematician Stephen Cole Kleene formalized the concept of a regular language.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] They came into common use with Unix text-processing utilities.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Different syntaxes for writing regular expressions have existed since the 1980s, one being the POSIX standard and another, widely used, being the Perl syntax.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions are used in search engines, in search and replace dialogs of word processors and text editors, in text processing utilities such as sed and AWK, and in lexical analysis.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions are supported in many programming languages.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Library implementations are often called an "engine", and many of these are available for reuse.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions originated in 1951, when mathematician Stephen Cole Kleene described regular languages using his mathematical notation called *regular events*.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] These arose in theoretical computer science, in the subfields of automata theory (models of computation) and the description and classification of formal languages, motivated by Kleene's attempt to describe early artificial neural networks.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions entered popular use from 1968 in two uses: pattern matching in a text editor and lexical analysis in a compiler.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Among the first appearances of regular expressions in program form was when Ken Thompson built Kleene's notation into the editor QED as a means to match patterns in text files.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by just-in-time compilation (JIT) to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System, an important early example of JIT compilation.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Around the same time that Thompson developed QED, a group of researchers including Douglas T.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Ross implemented a tool based on regular expressions that is used for lexical analysis in compiler design.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Many variations of these original forms of regular expressions were used in Unix programs at Bell Labs in the 1970s, including lex, sed, AWK, and expr, and in other programs such as vi, and Emacs (which has its own, incompatible syntax and behavior).
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Regexes were subsequently adopted by a wide range of programs, with these early forms standardized in the POSIX.2 standard in 1992.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] In the 1980s, the more complicated regexes arose in Perl, which originally derived from a regex library written by Henry Spencer (1986), who later wrote an implementation for Tcl called *Advanced Regular Expressions*.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The Tcl library is a hybrid NFA/DFA implementation with improved performance characteristics.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Software projects that have adopted Spencer's Tcl regular expression implementation include PostgreSQL.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Perl later expanded on Spencer's original library to add many new features.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Part of the effort in the design of Raku (formerly named Perl 6) is to improve Perl's regex integration, and to increase their scope and capabilities to allow the definition of parsing expression grammars.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The result is a mini-language called Raku rules, which are used to define Raku grammar as well as provide a tool to programmers in the language.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] These rules maintain existing features of Perl 5.x regexes, but also allow BNF-style definition of a recursive descent parser via sub-rules.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The use of regexes in structured information standards for document and database modeling started in the 1960s and expanded in the 1980s when industry standards like ISO SGML (precursored by ANSI "GCA 101-1983") consolidated.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The kernel of the structure specification language standards consists of regexes.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Its use is evident in the DTD element group syntax.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Prior to the use of regular expressions, many search languages allowed simple wildcards, for example "*" to match any sequence of characters, and "?" to match a single character.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Relics of this can be found today in the glob syntax for filenames, and in the SQL `LIKE` operator.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Starting in 1997, Philip Hazel developed PCRE (Perl Compatible Regular Expressions), which attempts to closely mimic Perl's regex functionality and is used by many modern tools including PHP and Apache HTTP Server.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Today, regexes are widely supported in programming languages, text processing programs (particularly lexers), advanced text editors, and some other programs.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Regex support is part of the standard library of many programming languages, including Java and Python, and is built into the syntax of others, including Perl and ECMAScript.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The phrase *regular expressions*, or *regexes*, is often used to mean the specific, standard textual syntax for representing patterns for matching text, as distinct from the mathematical notation described below.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Each character in a regular expression (that is, each character in the string describing its pattern) is either a metacharacter, having a special meaning, or a regular character that has a literal meaning.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] For example, in the regex `b.`, 'b' is a literal character that matches just 'b', while '.' is a metacharacter that matches every character except a newline.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Therefore, this regex matches, for example, 'b%', or 'bx', or 'b5'.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Together, metacharacters and literal characters can be used to identify text of a given pattern or process a number of instances of it.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Pattern matches may vary from a precise equality to a very general similarity, as controlled by the metacharacters.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] For example, `.` is a very general pattern, `[a-z]` (match all lowercase letters from 'a' to 'z') is less general and `b` is a precise pattern (matches just 'b').
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The metacharacter syntax is designed specifically to represent prescribed targets in a concise and flexible way to direct the automation of text processing of a variety of input data, in a form easy to type using a standard ASCII keyboard.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] A very simple case of a regular expression in this syntax is to locate a word spelled two different ways in a text editor; for example, the regular expression `seriali[sz]e` matches both "serialise" and "serialize".
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Wildcard characters also achieve this, but are more limited in what they can pattern, as they have fewer metacharacters and a simple language-base.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The usual context of wildcard characters is in globbing similar names in a list of files, whereas regexes are usually employed in applications that pattern-match text strings in general.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] For example, the regex `^[ \t]+|[ \t]+$` matches excess whitespace at the beginning or end of a line.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] A **regex processor** translates a regular expression in the above syntax into an internal representation that can be executed and matched against a string representing the text being searched in.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] One possible approach is the Thompson's construction algorithm to construct a nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA), which is then made deterministic and the resulting deterministic finite automaton (DFA) is run on the target text string to recognize substrings that match the regular expression.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The picture shows the NFA scheme `*N*(*s**)` obtained from the regular expression `*s**`, where *s* denotes a simpler regular expression in turn, which has already been recursively translated to the NFA *N*(*s*).
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] A regular expression, often called a *pattern*, specifies a set of strings required for a particular purpose.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] A simple way to specify a finite set of strings is to list its elements or members.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] However, there are often more concise ways: for example, the set containing the three strings "Handel", "Händel", and "Haendel" can be specified by the pattern `H(ä|ae?)ndel`; we say that this pattern *matches* each of the three strings.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] However, there can be many ways to write a regular expression for the same set of strings: for example, `(Hän|Han|Haen)del` also specifies the same set of three strings in this example.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Most formalisms provide the following operations to construct regular expressions.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] are equivalent patterns which both describe the set of "gray" or "grey".
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] , character, or group) specifies how many times the preceding element is allowed to repeat.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] matches any string that contains an "a", and then any character and then "b".
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] matches any string that contains an "a", and then the character "b" at some later point.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] These constructions can be combined to form arbitrarily complex expressions, much like one can construct arithmetical expressions from numbers and the operations +, −, ×, and ÷.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The precise syntax for regular expressions varies among tools and with context; more detail is given in § Syntax.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions describe regular languages in formal language theory.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] They have the same expressive power as regular grammars.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] But the language of regular expressions itself, is context-free language.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions consist of constants, which denote sets of strings, and operator symbols, which denote operations over these sets.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The following definition is standard, and found as such in most textbooks on formal language theory.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] To avoid parentheses, it is assumed that the Kleene star has the highest priority followed by concatenation, then alternation.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] If there is no ambiguity, then parentheses may be omitted.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] For example, `(ab)c` can be written as `abc`, and `a|(b(c*))` can be written as `a|bc*`.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Many textbooks use the symbols ∪, +, or ∨ for alternation instead of the vertical bar.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The derivative of a regular expression can be defined using the Brzozowski derivative.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The formal definition of regular expressions is minimal on purpose, and avoids defining `?` and `+`—these can be expressed as follows: `a+`=`aa*`, and `a?`=`(a|ε)`.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Sometimes the complement operator is added, to give a *generalized regular expression*; here *Rc* matches all strings over Σ* that do not match *R*.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] In principle, the complement operator is redundant, because it does not grant any more expressive power.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] However, it can make a regular expression much more concise—eliminating a single complement operator can cause a double exponential blow-up of its length.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions in this sense can express the regular languages, exactly the class of languages accepted by deterministic finite automata.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] There is, however, a significant difference in compactness.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Some classes of regular languages can only be described by deterministic finite automata whose size grows exponentially in the size of the shortest equivalent regular expressions.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The standard example here is the languages *Lk* consisting of all strings over the alphabet {*a*,*b*} whose *k*th-from-last letter equals *a*.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] On the one hand, a regular expression describing *L*4 is given by $(a\mid b)^{*}a(a\mid b)(a\mid b)(a\mid b)$ .
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] On the other hand, it is known that every deterministic finite automaton accepting the language *Lk* must have at least 2*k* states.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Luckily, there is a simple mapping from regular expressions to the more general nondeterministic finite automata (NFAs) that does not lead to such a blowup in size; for this reason NFAs are often used as alternative representations of regular languages.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] NFAs are a simple variation of the type-3 grammars of the Chomsky hierarchy.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] In the opposite direction, there are many languages easily described by a DFA that are not easily described by a regular expression.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] For instance, determining the validity of a given ISBN requires computing the remainder of an integer modulo 11, and can be easily implemented with an 11-state DFA.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] However, converting it to a regular expression results in a 2.14-megabyte file.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Given a regular expression, Thompson's construction algorithm computes an equivalent nondeterministic finite automaton.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] A conversion in the opposite direction is achieved by Kleene's algorithm.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Finally, many real-world "regular expression" engines implement features that cannot be described by the regular expressions in the sense of formal language theory; rather, they implement *regexes*.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] As seen in many of the examples above, there is more than one way to construct a regular expression to achieve the same results.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] It is possible to write an algorithm that, for two given regular expressions, decides whether the described languages are equal; the algorithm reduces each expression to a minimal deterministic finite state machine, and determines whether they are isomorphic (equivalent).
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] More generally, an equation *E*=*F* between regular-expression terms with variables holds if, and only if, its instantiation with different variables replaced by different symbol constants holds.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Every regular expression can be written solely in terms of the Kleene star and set unions over finite words.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] This is a surprisingly difficult problem.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] As simple as the regular expressions are, there is no method to systematically rewrite them to some normal form.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The lack of axiom in the past led to the star height problem.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] In 1991, Dexter Kozen axiomatized regular expressions as a Kleene algebra, using equational and Horn clause axioms.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Already in 1964, Redko had proved that no finite set of purely equational axioms can characterize the algebra of regular languages.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] A regex *pattern* matches a target *string*.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The pattern is composed of a sequence of *atoms*.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] An atom is a single point within the regex pattern which it tries to match to the target string.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The simplest atom is a literal, but grouping parts of the pattern to match an atom will require using `( )` as metacharacters.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] A match is made, not when all the atoms of the string are matched, but rather when all the pattern atoms in the regex have matched.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The idea is to make a small pattern of characters stand for a large number of possible strings, rather than compiling a large list of all the literal possibilities.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Depending on the regex processor there are about fourteen metacharacters, characters that may or may not have their literal character meaning, depending on context, or whether they are "escaped", i.e. preceded by an escape sequence, in this case, the backslash `\`.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The usual characters that become metacharacters when escaped are `dswDSW` and `N`.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] When entering a regex in a programming language, they may be represented as a usual string literal, hence usually quoted; this is common in C, Java, and Python for instance, where the regex `re` is entered as `"re"`.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] However, they are often written with slashes as delimiters, as in `/re/` for the regex `re`.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] A similar convention is used in sed, where search and replace is given by `s/re/replacement/` and patterns can be joined with a comma to specify a range of lines as in `/re1/,/re2/`.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] This notation is particularly well known due to its use in Perl, where it forms part of the syntax distinct from normal string literals.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] In some cases, such as sed and Perl, alternative delimiters can be used to avoid collision with contents, and to avoid having to escape occurrences of the delimiter character in the contents.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] For example, in sed the command `s,/,X,` will replace a `/` with an `X`, using commas as delimiters.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The IEEE POSIX standard has three sets of compliance: **BRE** (Basic Regular Expressions), **ERE** (Extended Regular Expressions), and **SRE** (Simple Regular Expressions).
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] SRE is deprecated, in favor of BRE, as both provide backward compatibility.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The subsection below covering the *character classes* applies to both BRE and ERE.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] ERE adds `?`, `+`, and `|`, and it removes the need to escape the metacharacters `( )` and `{ }`, which are *required* in BRE.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Furthermore, as long as the POSIX standard syntax for regexes is adhered to, there can be, and often is, additional syntax to serve specific (yet POSIX compliant) applications.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Although POSIX.2 leaves some implementation specifics undefined, BRE and ERE provide a "standard" which has since been adopted as the default syntax of many tools, where the choice of BRE or ERE modes is usually a supported option.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] For example, GNU `grep` has the following options: "`grep -E`" for ERE, and "`grep -G`" for BRE (the default), and "`grep -P`" for Perl regexes.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Perl regexes have become a de facto standard, having a rich and powerful set of atomic expressions.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Perl has no "basic" or "extended" levels.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] As in POSIX EREs, `( )` and `{ }` are treated as metacharacters unless escaped; other metacharacters are known to be literal or symbolic based on context alone.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Additional functionality includes lazy matching, backreferences, named capture groups, and recursive patterns.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] In the POSIX standard, Basic Regular Syntax (**BRE**) requires that the metacharacters `( )` and `{ }` be designated `\(\)` and `\{\}`, whereas Extended Regular Syntax (**ERE**) does not.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] According to Russ Cox, the POSIX specification requires ambiguous subexpressions to be handled in a way different from Perl's.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The committee replaced Perl's rules with one that is simple to explain, but the new "simple" rules are actually more complex to implement: they were incompatible with pre-existing tooling and made it essentially impossible to define a "lazy match" (see below) extension.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] As a result, very few programs actually implement the POSIX subexpression rules (even when they implement other parts of the POSIX syntax).
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The meaning of metacharacters escaped with a backslash is reversed for some characters in the POSIX Extended Regular Expression (**ERE**) syntax.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] With this syntax, a backslash causes the metacharacter to be treated as a literal character.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] POSIX Extended Regular Expressions can often be used with modern Unix utilities by including the command line flag *-E*.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The character class is the most basic regex concept after a literal match.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] It makes one small sequence of characters match a larger set of characters.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] For example, `[A-Z]` could stand for any uppercase letter in the English alphabet, and `\d` could mean any digit.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Character classes apply to both POSIX levels.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] When specifying a range of characters, such as `[a-Z]` (i.e. lowercase *`a`* to uppercase *`Z`*), the computer's locale settings determine the contents by the numeric ordering of the character encoding.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] They could store digits in that sequence, or the ordering could be *abc...zABC...Z*, or *aAbBcC...zZ*.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] So the POSIX standard defines a character class, which will be known by the regex processor installed.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] POSIX character classes can only be used within bracket expressions.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] For example, `[[:upper:]ab]` matches the uppercase letters and lowercase "a" and "b".
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] An additional non-POSIX class understood by some tools is `[:word:]`, which is usually defined as `[:alnum:]` plus underscore.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] This reflects the fact that in many programming languages these are the characters that may be used in identifiers.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Note that what the POSIX regex standards call *character classes* are commonly referred to as *POSIX character classes* in other regex flavors which support them.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] With most other regex flavors, the term *character class* is used to describe what POSIX calls *bracket expressions*.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Because of its expressive power and (relative) ease of reading, many other utilities and programming languages have adopted syntax similar to Perl's—for example, Java, JavaScript, Julia, Python, Ruby, Qt, Microsoft's .NET Framework, and XML Schema.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Some languages and tools such as Boost and PHP support multiple regex flavors.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Perl-derivative regex implementations are not identical and usually implement a subset of features found in Perl 5.0, released in 1994.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Perl sometimes does incorporate features initially found in other languages.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] For example, Perl 5.10 implements syntactic extensions originally developed in PCRE and Python.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] In Python and some other implementations (e.g.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Java), the three common quantifiers (`*`, `+`, and `?`) are greedy by default because they match as many characters as possible.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] matches the entire line (because the entire line begins and ends with a double-quote) instead of matching only the first part, `"Ganymede,"`.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The aforementioned quantifiers may, however, be made *lazy* or *minimal* or *reluctant*, matching as few characters as possible, by appending a question mark: `".+?"` matches only `"Ganymede,"`.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] matches the entire line, the regex `".*+"` does *not match at all*, because `.*+` consumes the entire input, including the final `"`.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Thus, possessive quantifiers are most useful with negated character classes, e.g.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] `"[^"]*+"`, which matches `"Ganymede,"` when applied to the same string.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Another common extension serving the same function is atomic grouping, which disables backtracking for a parenthesized group.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] For example, while ^(wi|w)i$ matches both wi and wii, ^(?>wi|w)i$ only matches wii because the engine is forbidden from backtracking and so cannot try setting the group to "w" after matching "wi".
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Possessive quantifiers are easier to implement than greedy and lazy quantifiers, and are typically more efficient at runtime.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] IETF RFC 9485 describes "I-Regexp: An Interoperable Regular Expression Format".
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] It specifies a limited subset of regular-expression idioms designed to be interoperable, i.e. produce the same effect, in a large number of regular-expression libraries.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] I-Regexp is also limited to matching, i.e. providing a true or false match between a regular expression and a given piece of text.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Thus, it lacks advanced features such as capture groups, lookahead, and backreferences.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Many features found in virtually all modern regular expression libraries provide an expressive power that exceeds the regular languages.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] For example, many implementations allow grouping subexpressions with parentheses and recalling the value they match in the same expression (*backreferences*).
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] This means that, among other things, a pattern can match strings of repeated words like "papa" or "WikiWiki", called *squares* in formal language theory.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The pattern for these strings is `(.+)\1`.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The language of squares is not regular, nor is it context-free, due to the pumping lemma.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] However, pattern matching with an unbounded number of backreferences, as supported by numerous modern tools, is still context sensitive.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The general problem of matching any number of backreferences is NP-complete, and the execution time for known algorithms grows exponentially by the number of backreference groups used.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] However, many tools, libraries, and engines that provide such constructions still use the term *regular expression* for their patterns.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] This has led to a nomenclature where the term regular expression has different meanings in formal language theory and pattern matching.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] For this reason, some people have taken to using the term *regex*, *regexp*, or simply *pattern* to describe the latter.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Other features not found in describing regular languages include assertions.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] These include the ubiquitous `^` and `$`, used since at least 1970, as well as some more sophisticated extensions like lookaround that appeared in 1994.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Lookarounds define the surrounding of a match and do not spill into the match itself, a feature only relevant for the use case of string searching.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Some of them can be simulated in a regular language by treating the surroundings as a part of the language as well.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The look-ahead assertions `(?=...)` and `(?!...)` have been attested since at least 1994, starting with Perl 5.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The lookbehind assertions `(?<=...)` and `(?<!...)` are attested since 1997 in a commit by Ilya Zakharevich to Perl 5.005.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] There are at least three different algorithms that decide whether and how a given regex matches a string.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The oldest and fastest relies on a result in formal language theory that allows every nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA) to be transformed into a deterministic finite automaton (DFA).
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The DFA can be constructed explicitly and then run on the resulting input string one symbol at a time.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Constructing the DFA for a regular expression of size *m* has the time and memory cost of *O*(2*m*), but it can be run on a string of size *n* in time *O*(*n*).
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Note that the size of the expression is the size after abbreviations, such as numeric quantifiers, have been expanded.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] An alternative approach is to simulate the NFA directly, essentially building each DFA state on demand and then discarding it at the next step.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] This keeps the DFA implicit and avoids the exponential construction cost, but running cost rises to *O*(*mn*).
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The explicit approach is called the DFA algorithm and the implicit approach the NFA algorithm.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Adding caching to the NFA algorithm is often called the "lazy DFA" algorithm, or just the DFA algorithm without making a distinction.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] These algorithms are fast, but using them for recalling grouped subexpressions, lazy quantification, and similar features is tricky.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Modern implementations include the re1-re2-sregex family based on Cox's code.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] The third algorithm is to match the pattern against the input string by backtracking.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] This algorithm is commonly called NFA, but this terminology can be confusing.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Its running time can be exponential, which simple implementations exhibit when matching against expressions like `(a|aa)*b` that contain both alternation and unbounded quantification and force the algorithm to consider an exponentially increasing number of sub-cases.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] This behavior can cause a security problem called Regular expression Denial of Service (ReDoS).
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Although backtracking implementations only give an exponential guarantee in the worst case, they provide much greater flexibility and expressive power.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] For example, any implementation which allows the use of backreferences, or implements the various extensions introduced by Perl, must include some kind of backtracking.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Some implementations try to provide the best of both algorithms by first running a fast DFA algorithm, and revert to a potentially slower backtracking algorithm only when a backreference is encountered during the match.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] GNU grep (and the underlying gnulib DFA) uses such a strategy.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Sublinear runtime algorithms have been achieved using Boyer-Moore (BM) based algorithms and related DFA optimization techniques such as the reverse scan.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] GNU grep, which supports a wide variety of POSIX syntaxes and extensions, uses BM for a first-pass prefiltering, and then uses an implicit DFA.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Wu agrep, which implements approximate matching, combines the prefiltering into the DFA in BDM (backward DAWG matching).
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] NR-grep's BNDM extends the BDM technique with Shift-Or bit-level parallelism.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] A few theoretical alternatives to backtracking for backreferences exist, and their "exponents" are tamer in that they are only related to the number of backreferences, a fixed property of some regexp languages such as POSIX.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] One naive method that duplicates a non-backtracking NFA for each backreference note has a complexity of ⁠ ${\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+2})$ ⁠ time and ⁠ ${\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+1})$ ⁠ space for a haystack of length n and k backreferences in the RegExp.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Theoretical work based on memory automata gives a tighter bound based on "active" variable nodes used, and a polynomial possibility for some backreferenced regexps.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] In theoretical terms, any token set can be matched by regular expressions as long as it is pre-defined.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] In terms of historical implementations, regexes were originally written to use ASCII characters as their token set though regex libraries have supported numerous other character sets.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Many modern regex engines offer at least some support for Unicode.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] In most respects it makes no difference what the character set is, but some issues do arise when extending regexes to support Unicode.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p01] Most general-purpose programming languages support regex capabilities, either natively or via libraries.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] Regexes are useful in a wide variety of text processing tasks, and more generally string processing, where the data need not be textual.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] Common applications include data validation, data scraping (especially web scraping), data wrangling, simple parsing, the production of syntax highlighting systems, and many other tasks.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] Some high-end desktop publishing software has the ability to use regexes to automatically apply text styling, saving the person doing the layout from laboriously doing this by hand for anything that can be matched by a regex.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] For example, by defining a character style that makes text into small caps and then using the regex `[A-Z]{4,}` to apply that style, any word of four or more consecutive capital letters will be automatically rendered as small caps instead.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] While regexes would be useful on Internet search engines, processing them across the entire database could consume excessive computer resources depending on the complexity and design of the regex.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] Although in many cases system administrators can run regex-based queries internally, most search engines do not offer regex support to the public.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] Notable exceptions include Google Code Search and Exalead.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] However, Google Code Search was shut down in January 2012.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] The specific syntax rules vary depending on the specific implementation, programming language, or library in use.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] Additionally, the functionality of regex implementations can vary between versions.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] Because regexes can be difficult to both explain and understand without examples, interactive websites for testing regexes are a useful resource for learning regexes by experimentation.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] This section provides a basic description of some of the properties of regexes by way of illustration.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] The following conventions are used in the examples.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] Standard POSIX regular expressions are different.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] Unless otherwise indicated, the following examples conform to the Perl programming language, release 5.8.8, January 31, 2006.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] This means that other implementations may lack support for some parts of the syntax shown here (e.g. basic vs. extended regex, `\( \)` vs.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] The syntax and conventions used in these examples coincide with that of other programming environments as well.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] Regular expressions can often be created ("induced" or "learned") based on a set of example strings.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] This is known as the induction of regular languages and is part of the general problem of grammar induction in computational learning theory.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] Formally, given examples of strings in a regular language, and perhaps also given examples of strings *not* in that regular language, it is possible to induce a grammar for the language, i.e., a regular expression that generates that language.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] Not all regular languages can be induced in this way (see language identification in the limit), but many can.
[src:promql/regular-expression-p02] For example, the set of examples {1, 10, 100}, and negative set (of counterexamples) {11, 1001, 101, 0} can be used to induce the regular expression 1⋅0* (1 followed by zero or more 0s).
[src:promql/time-series-database] A **time series database** is a software system that is optimized for storing and serving time series through associated pairs of time(s) and value(s).
[src:promql/time-series-database] In some fields, *time series* may be called profiles, curves, traces or trends.
[src:promql/time-series-database] Several early time series databases are associated with industrial applications which could efficiently store measured values from sensory equipment (also referred to as data historians), but now are used in support of a much wider range of applications.
[src:promql/time-series-database] In many cases, the repositories of time-series data will utilize compression algorithms to manage the data efficiently.
[src:promql/time-series-database] Although it is possible to store time-series data in many different database types, the design of these systems with time as a key index is distinctly different from relational databases which reduce discrete relationships through referential models.
[src:promql/time-series-database] Time series datasets are relatively large and uniform compared to other datasets―usually being composed of a timestamp and associated data.
[src:promql/time-series-database] Time series datasets can also have fewer relationships between data entries in different tables and don't require indefinite storage of entries.
[src:promql/time-series-database] The unique properties of time series datasets mean that time series databases can provide significant improvements in storage space and performance over general purpose databases.
[src:promql/time-series-database] For instance, due to the uniformity of time series data, specialized compression algorithms can provide improvements over regular compression algorithms designed to work on less uniform data.
[src:promql/time-series-database] Time series databases can also be configured to regularly delete (or downsample) old data, unlike regular databases which are designed to store data indefinitely.
[src:promql/time-series-database] Special database indices can also provide boosts in query performance.
[src:promql/time-series-database] Time series databases are commonly designed for append-heavy workloads, where large numbers of measurements or events are continuously written together with timestamps.
[src:promql/time-series-database] Specialized time series management systems have been developed for data from monitoring, automation, the Internet of Things, and cyber-physical systems, where data may be produced at high velocity and in large volumes.
[src:promql/time-series-database] Common design goals include high-throughput data ingestion, low-latency queries over time ranges, efficient compression, and support for aggregation or downsampling over time windows.
[src:promql/time-series-database] Many systems also organize data by tags, devices, sensors, or other metadata, so that users can retrieve measurements by both time range and source.
[src:promql/time-series-database] Time series databases are used in application areas where data is collected continuously over time.
[src:promql/time-series-database] Examples include industrial monitoring, operational historians, infrastructure and application monitoring, Internet of Things sensor data, energy systems, financial market data, and scientific measurements.
[src:promql/time-series-database] In monitoring applications, time series database systems may need to process large amounts of sensor or metric data in real time, execute continuous queries, and support analytical tasks such as data exploration, anomaly detection, predictive modeling, trend analysis, and missing-value recovery.
[src:promql/time-series-database] Time series databases are often used as storage and query systems for downstream analytical tasks, including forecasting, anomaly detection, imputation, and pattern matching.
[src:promql/time-series-database] Some systems also integrate analytical or machine-learning functions closer to the database layer, allowing users to invoke forecasting or anomaly detection through database query interfaces such as SQL.
[src:promql/time-series-database] Recent research in time series analysis has also explored large pre-trained models for tasks such as forecasting, imputation, and anomaly detection.
[src:promql/time-series-database] These models are usually discussed as analytical methods for time series data rather than as defining features of time series databases.
[src:promql/time-series-database] The following database systems have functionality optimized for handling time series data.
